# Cloudflare Workers static-assets header rules (same format as Cloudflare Pages;
# read from the root of the [assets] directory, i.e. dist/_headers). Astro copies
# public/ verbatim into dist/, so this file ships as dist/_headers on every build.
#
# ── Why this file exists (now belt-and-suspenders) ───────────────────────────
# History: the recurring "nebelhaus.com has no CSS on iOS" bug. Every page once
# pulled its entire stylesheet from a single content-hashed file
# (/_astro/index.<hash>.css) with no inline fallback; each deploy published a NEW
# filename and deleted the old one, so a browser serving a *stale cached HTML
# document* pointed at an /_astro/<oldhash>.css that no longer existed → 404 →
# a completely unstyled page. iOS WebKit (Safari AND every WKWebView, including
# the Instagram/Facebook in-app browsers) caches top-level HTML heuristically and
# far more aggressively than desktop Chrome/Firefox, so it hit this first and
# hardest — and it kept returning because must-revalidate only works if the
# client honors it, which those WebViews don't reliably do.
#
# THE DURABLE CURE now lives in astro.config.mjs (`build.inlineStylesheets:
# 'always'`): the CSS is inlined into every page's <head>, so there is no
# external main stylesheet to 404 and rendering no longer depends on any cache
# header. This file is kept as a secondary guard — it still keeps hashed JS fresh
# (a stale script 404 degrades interactivity without unstyling the page) and
# revalidates HTML, which is cheap and correct.
#
# ── The policy ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Make HTML always revalidate, and make the hashed assets truly immutable:
#
#   • HTML (/*)          max-age=0, must-revalidate → the browser must check with
#                        the origin on every navigation. Unchanged pages come back
#                        as a cheap 304 (cached HTML reused, its hashes still
#                        valid); a redeploy returns fresh HTML with the new hash.
#                        Either way a browser can never render a document that
#                        points at a deleted stylesheet.
#   • /_astro/*          Fingerprinted by content, so the name changes when the
#                        bytes change → safe to cache for a year, immutable, never
#                        revalidated. This keeps the win the hashing is meant to
#                        give even though the broad /* rule above also matches.
#
# ── The one gotcha (do not "simplify" this) ──────────────────────────────────
# wrangler MERGES every matching rule, and when two matching rules both *set* the
# same header it APPENDS a second value rather than overriding — an /_astro asset
# matches both /* and /_astro/* and would get a corrupt, self-contradictory
# `Cache-Control: ...max-age=0..., ...max-age=31536000...`. The `! Cache-Control`
# line first UNSETS what /* added so the immutable value is the only one that
# survives. Rules apply top-to-bottom, so /* MUST stay above /_astro/*.

/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

/_astro/*
  ! Cache-Control
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
